      "example": "It isn't distance that kills a language inside you — it's comfort. The first tongue sits in the body like a warm coat; the second, for years, feels like a borrowed suit that never quite fits. So we retreat. We speak the new language only when forced, rehearse the safe phrases, and call that fluency. And yet a second language, used in earnest, does something the first cannot: it hands you a second self. In English I am, arguably, a slightly braver person — blunter, drier, quicker to say the unsayable, because the words cost me effort and I spend them with care. The mistakes still come, heavy as rain. I make them, wince, and go on. Never, in my own language, have I had to fight so hard simply to mean what I mean. That fight, it turns out, is the whole reward. I did not learn English to sound like someone else. I learned it to find out who else I might be."
